  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Epitaph for Princess Sunyeong, Kim of the Wang House
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Kim lineage rose to nobility in the earliest days of Silla. Legend tells that the golden coffer descended from heaven, and they took this as their surname; others say they descended from the line of Xiaohao of the Golden Heaven, and thus adopted the name. Their descendants held the throne for ages, until King Gyeongshun, when they met the fortunes of our nation's sacred king and, knowing heaven's mandate had turned, brought their lands in submission. Many of their clan migrated here, receiving grace and office, generation after generation proving loyal and diligent, growing ever greater with time. In recent times there was a Prime Minister, Fengmao by name, who held the post of Wenxia Pingzhang. He fathered Pingzhang Taishui, who fathered Deputy Director of密直 Qingson, who fathered Mizhi承旨 Xin. The承旨took a wife from the Yun house; her father, Pan, was Judge of the Greater Storehouse. The late Princess Sunyeong was his youngest daughter. At fourteen, noble and virtuous, she was betrothed to Wang On, the late Prince of Yeseong, fourth son of Prince Hyeon and younger brother of King Munjong, tenth generation grandson of the Prince of Pyongyang. The family had long been close to the throne, inheriting ranks of duke and marquis. Her uncle, the Prince of Daebangang, served the Mongol emperor at court with young men of the realm, and the Son of Heaven, delighting in their service, showered them with gifts numbering hundreds yearly.

    The Princess became a widow before thirty, with three young sons and a daughter to raise alone. She educated and nurtured them all to adulthood, and lived to see grandchildren. Her eldest son Jun became Duke of Hwae'an, the next Yu became Duke of Changwon, and the third Soo became Lord of Nangrang. She had eight grandsons: Jeung became Lord of Bonyeong, Dang and Seo became Judges, Hyeong and Jeong she also bore; the rest were still young.

    In the era of延祐 to 至治, imperial order went forth seeking the daughters of the Wang house. Her daughter was chosen, and married to the Left Chancellor of the Central Secretariat for the River South region, and was made Princess of Jeong'an. When her beloved daughter departed for distant lands, grief and worry seized the Princess and brought her low. Thereafter her condition waxed and waned until the third year of Woontong, when illness deepened and medicine availed not. In the ninth month on the day of을유 she passed away, aged fifty-five.

    Before this time, the sons and daughters of our land were taken westward without ceasing, and even those of royal blood could not escape this sorrow. When mother and child parted, their reunion lay beyond all hope, and the pain sank deep into the bone, bringing many to their graves with sickness and despair. What greater injustice could exist under heaven? Yet now the present emperor, heeding the words of the Censorate, has forbidden this practice. The old and young throughout the realm rejoice in this wisdom and mercy, and dance with joy—all save the Princess, who did not live to see it. Alas, how sorrowful!

    On the day of甲辰 of this month, she was laid to rest at Daedeok Plain, joining the Duke in the ancestral shrine. The king appointed officials to oversee the rites. The Dukes of Hwae'an and Changwon performed the ceremonies with perfect propriety, though the youngest could not attend from the capital. These two lords loved learning and honored guests, bearing themselves as noble sons of a peaceful age. They were versed in the rites and records of family and state, and thus the Wang kinsmen who sought to preserve their traditions gathered around them. Is this not the fruit of a mother's wise instruction? When, in the second year of Hwanggyeong, the King first received his rank and ascended the throne, the Duke of Hwae'an attended him constantly with flawless protocol. The royal grace extended to his forebears, and thus was granted the title "Sunyeong." By further decree, monthly provisions were made equal to those of the eldest princess—a special honor indeed.

    Scholars have remarked that since Kim was the consort of a Great Duke, her title should not be the same as those borne by royal daughters; surely some will contend this point. I have long served the senior lord, and though my nature is dull, I dared not refuse when asked to inscribe this epitaph. I have set down plainly the descent and fate of her house and the words of the scholars, hiding nothing.

    The inscription reads:

    The mountain stands firm in its place,
    The waters flow fair to the shore—
    Where good omens blessed the earth,
    We laid her to peaceful rest.
    Whose grave lies here? Whose bones repose?
    The Princess and the Duke as one.
    When thousand years have passed away,
    Still shall men read what is written here.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Princess Sunyeong lived during the Goryeo period under Mongol influence; her daughter was taken to serve at the Yuan court, a practice that caused great suffering among Goryeo families.
  - key: ''
    value: The inscription's closing couplet expresses the commemoration of both the Princess and her husband, the Duke, through their shared burial and ancestral rites.
